			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="717">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>The other day I was sitting in my car at a park close to my workplace, eating my lunch and reading Rob Keast&rsquo;s essay &ldquo;<a href="/article/4504">The Nature Trail Closest to My House</a>&rdquo; [February 2011]. As a native of the Los Angeles suburbs I can relate to his longing for nature. I too have felt constricted by the concrete jungle.</p>

<p>After finishing his piece, I decided to get out of my car and take a walk. I spied an old craggy tree I have passed by many times but have mostly ignored. It is a grand old tree with withering branches that has seen decades of life. I didn&rsquo;t go so far as to caress it, but I did speak to it and let it know how beautiful it was. On that afternoon I felt, like Keast, that I belonged right where I was.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Christine Iseri<br>Lakewood, California</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="718">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I commend Rob Keast for writing &ldquo;The Nature Trail Closest to My House.&rdquo; No matter how sophisticated our understanding of the natural world, it is all too easy for us to overinvest in an elaborate outdoors experience &mdash; be it swimming with dolphins, hiking in the Grand Canyon, or watching polar bears in Manitoba. In his lyrical elevation of the quotidian, Keast reminds us that the most rewarding encounters are nearest home.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">David L. Gorsline<br>Reston, Virginia</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

					</div>

				<div class="text-center">
			<button class="b b-1 xsmall js-b-readmore-correspondence" data-collapsible="#article-correspondences" data-label="Read More Letters">Read More Letters</button>
		</div>
			</div>
    
